2. ITEM WITHDRAWN ON 11/13/18: Proposed 2019 Summer School Program and Extended School Year; BUDGETED: YES, TITLE I AND GENERAL FUNDS
Meeting
Nov 13, 2018 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Action
Fiscal Impact
Yes
Dollar Amount
$2,006,476.00
Budgeted
Yes
Budget Source
Title I and General Funds

RECOMMENDATION: Approve the proposed 2019 Summer School Program and Extended School Year as described below. 

 

It is proposed that a 2019 Summer School program be offered to general education students in Grades 9-12 for credit recovery (D and F make-up in core subjects). The program will be offered at an estimated nine high school sites, to be located Districtwide. Approximately 5,000 students in Grades 9-12 receive F grades in core subjects at the first semester, which would render them eligible for the program. Proposed program dates are June 17, 2019 through July 26, 2019. Transportation will not be provided.

 

The California Code of Regulations Section 3043(f) requires that Extended School Year (ESY) services be provided for each individual with exceptional needs who has unique needs and requires special education and related services in excess of the regular academic year. Such individuals have disabilities which are likely to continue indefinitely or for a prolonged period, and interruption of the pupil’s educational programming may cause regression, when coupled with limited recoupment capacity, rendering it impossible or unlikely that the pupil will attain the level of self-sufficiency and independence that would otherwise be expected in view of his or her disabling condition. The lack of clear evidence of such factors may not be used to deny an individual an ESY program if the student’s Individual Education Program (IEP) team determines the need for such a program and includes ESY in the IEP. The proposed program for high school students is June 17, 2019 through July 26, 2019, and for elementary and middle school students is July 24, 2019 through August 18, 2019. Transportation services will be provided.

 

It is proposed that summer programs for both general education students and students with disabilities be offered at Districtwide sites. Tentative high school sites are: Clairemont, Garfield, Hoover, iHigh, Lincoln, Morse, San Diego High, Serra, and Twain. Due to major construction projects in the District, all final host Summer School and ESY sites have not yet been selected. Final sites will be determined after working with PPO/Facilities to ensure no conflicts, in collaboration with the Area Superintendents, and in consultation with the Physical Plant Operations and Transportation Departments, taking into consideration actual geographic patterns of ESY eligible students.

 

FISCAL IMPACT:

 

The approximate cost of the 2019 Summer School program described above is $2,006,476.00 which includes $2,004,476.00 for teacher, counselor, librarian, and administrator salaries, office/clerical, security, custodial, and technical support, and supplies for the summer credit recovery program; and $2,000 for the summer graduation ceremony for seniors who complete their graduation requirements during Summer School.

 

This cost estimate is based on the maximum number of students eligible for the program, as indicated by fall 2018 data. Should the number of eligible students decline during the spring 2019 semester, or if fewer eligible students actually attend Summer School, teachers will be released at the end of the first program week and classes will be consolidated to reduce costs. Title 1 Funds have been identified for the Summer School program. Cost breakdown for each program is summarized below:

  • Credit Recovery: Grades 9-12, $2,004,476.00, budget string: XXXX-30105-00-XXXX-100-1110-01000-0170
  • Summer Graduation Ceremony: $2,000; budget string: 5593-00070-00-5619-2700-0000-01000-0000 (General Fund Unrestricted).

The approximate cost of the 2019 ESY program described above for students with disabilities is $3,200,000. The estimate includes program services for infant/early childhood (birth-five years old), elementary, middle, high school, and the TRACE Program (transition program for 18-22 year olds).

 

This cost estimate is based on the maximum number of students eligible for the program, as indicated by fall 2018 data. Should the number of eligible students decline during the spring 2019 semester, or if fewer eligible students actually attend ESY, teachers will be released at the end of the first program week and classes will be consolidated to reduce costs. Special Education Extended School Year (65005) and Special Education Transportation (72400) funds have been identified for the program.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: $2,031,092, for the general education Summer School program, and $4,717,607.00 for the ESY program

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: No additional staffing is required. Summer School provides additional work opportunities for existing 10-month certificated and classified staff. Per Article 17 of the San Diego Education Association (SDEA) Collective Negotiations Contract, announcements of Summer School certificated job opportunities must be posted by March 1.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: The District Advisory Council (DAC) has been notified, and will review the proposed allocations at its meeting on November 14, 2018.

5. Resolution in the Matter of Recognizing November 2018 as Native American Indian Heritage Month
Meeting
Nov 13, 2018 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Action (Consent)
Fiscal Impact
No

RECOMMENDATION: Approve resolution in the matter of recognizing November 2018 as Native American Indian Heritage Month in San Diego Unified.

 

BACKGROUND: On August 3, 1990, George H. W. Bush, President of the United States, declared the month of November as Native American Indian Heritage Month.

 

The President authorized and called upon federal, state, and local governments, groups and organizations, and the people of the United States, to observe November with appropriate programs, ceremonies, and activities.

 

The contributions of Native American Indians to this nation’s government, history, and culture are as numerous and varied as the tribes themselves.

 

San Diego County has 19 different Native American Indian reservations, more than any other county in the United States.

 

Approximately 25,000 Native Americans live in San Diego County, most coming from four local tribes—Kumeyaay/Diegueño, Luiseño, Cupeño, and Cahuilla.

 

The San Diego Unified School District, through the Family Engagement Department, as well as through all offices and schools sites, promotes equity for all students and will continue to provide tutoring, career guidance, mental health support, cultural awareness, leadership development, and cultural enrichment programs for Native American students.

 

The commemorative month aims to provide a platform for Native American Indians to share their culture, traditions, music, crafts, dance, and ways and concepts of life.

 

The Indian Education Program and the Native American Indian community have made and continue to provide significant and important contributions to the community and the nation as a whole.

6. Resolution in the Matter of Recognizing November 16, 2018, as National Parent/Family Involvement Day
Meeting
Nov 13, 2018 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type

Fiscal Impact
No

RECOMMENDATION: Approve resolution recognizing November 15, 2018, as National Parent/Family Involvement Day. The San Diego Unified School District recognizes the importance of this day, and its goals of increasing overall student achievement through family engagement.

 

BACKGROUND: In 2012, the San Diego Unified Council of PTAs introduced the first National Parent Involvement day for San Diego Unified School District.

 

The San Diego Unified School District, the San Diego Unified Council of PTAs, and the broader education field recognize there are many significant caregivers in children’s lives not adequately represented by the term “parent,” therefore the term “family” is also used to celebrate this day.

 

The San Diego Unified District’s Family Engagement Department and the San Diego Unified Council of PTAs jointly support the district’s Local Control Accountability Plan (LCAP) Goal 5:  Family and Community Engagement with Highly Regarded Neighborhood Schools that Serve Students, Families and Communities.

 

The San Diego Unified School District and the San Diego Unified Council of PTAs partner to recognize National Parent/Family Involvement Day at district schools and all of the existing avenues for family engagement.

 

The San Diego Unified School District and San Diego Unified Council of PTAs are catalyzed by more than 40 years of research confirmed by experience that strong family, school, and community partnerships to support student learning, both at school and at home, increase overall student achievement, attendance, credit acquisition, graduation rates, life outcomes, and school effectiveness.

 

The mission of PTA is to make every child’s potential a reality by engaging and empowering families and communities to advocate for all children.

 

Schools will host an event during the week of November 12-16, 2018, to celebrate National Parent/Family Involvement Day, to honor the powerful contributions that families make to support the success of students and to reinforce awareness of the invaluable role that families play in supporting student learning and public education, and honor their contributions to student success.

 

On addition to recognizing the role families play as invaluable allies in student success, secondary goals of National Parent/Family Involvement Day include identifying family and community leaders whose efforts will help schools increase family engagement, building strong partnerships linked to student learning.

Nov 13, 2018 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type

Fiscal Impact

RECOMMENDATION:  Designate the date and time of the 2018 Annual Organizational Meeting of the San Diego Unified School District Board of Education as Tuesday, December 11, 2018.  The meeting will begin at 5:00 p.m., in the Eugene Brucker Education Center auditorium located at 4100 Normal Street, San Diego, California 92103.  At the annual organizational meeting, the board will elect the officers (President and Vice President), for the term effective December 12, 2018 through December 10, 2019.  The annual organizational item to elect the Board Officers will be heard at the conclusion of the meeting after all other business items are complete.

 

FISCAL IMPACT:  None.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT:  None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING:  None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE:  Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND:  Education Code section 35143 requires the governing board of each school district to hold an annual organizational meeting. In a year in which a regular election for governing board members is conducted, the meeting shall be held on a day within a 15-day period that commences with the date upon which a governing board member elected at that election takes office. Organizational meetings in years in which no such regular election for governing board members is conducted shall be held during the same 15-day period on the calendar. Unless otherwise provided by rule of the governing board, the day and time of the annual meeting shall be selected by the board at its regular meeting held immediately prior to the first day of such 15-day period, and the board shall notify the county superintendent of schools of the day and time selected. 

 

Board Bylaw section 1002 requires the President and Vice President of the Board of Education to be elected from the members of the Board at the Board's annual meeting held at a public meeting of the Board of Education after 10:00 a.m. on the first Monday after the first day of December, or as soon thereafter as may be practicable.

The educational program described in the Empower charter petition includes the following characteristics:

  • An inquiry-based academic program with a focus on fitness and health that incorporates Howard Gardners Five Minds for the Future.

  • A Spanish Immersion program to produce bilingual, bi-literate students and equips students with essential tools for an interconnected, global society.

  • Writing-centered curriculum.

Empower is seeking renewal of its charter for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2019, and ending June 30, 2024. Staff recommends that the Board grant the charter renewal with the following clarification as noted:

 

1. Revise the Admission Requirement section as detailed below:

 

Revise the admission preferences to the following order:

  1. Siblings of current students.

  2. Children of founding members or founding trustees of the Charter School (not to exceed 10% of total enrollment)

  3. Children of current full-time staff members

  4. To maintain and strengthen the dual immersion model, Spanish-speaking students will be recruited and will be given preferential admission up to 50% of the positions available in each grade. (we are checking on this item)

  5. All other students residing within the boundaries of San Diego Unified School District

  6. All other students residing outside of the boundaries of San Diego Unified School District

RENEWAL ANALYSIS

 

When considering a petition for renewal, pursuant to Title 5 of the California Code of Regulations section 11966.4(b)(1), the district governing board shall consider the past performance of the schools academics, finances, and operations in evaluating the likelihood of future success, along with future plans for improvement, if any.

 

ACADEMICS

 

As the charter granting authority, pursuant to Education Code section 47607(a)(3)(A), the district shall consider increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils served by the charter school as the most important factor in determining whether to grant a charter renewal. For purposes of this section, all groups of pupils served by the charter school means a numerically significant pupil subgroup served by the charter school, as defined in Education Code section 52052(a)(3).[1]

 

Per Education Code section 47607(b), a charter school shall meet at least one of the following criteria before receiving a renewal:[2]

  1. Attained its Academic Performance Index (API) growth target in the prior year or in two of the last three years both schoolwide and for all groups of pupils served by the charter school.

  2. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API in the prior year or in two of the last three years.

  3. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API for a demographically comparable school in the prior year or in two of the last three years.

  4. The entity that granted the charter determines that the academic performance of the charter school is at least equal to the academic performance of the public schools that the charter school pupils would otherwise have been required to attend, as well as the academic performance of the schools in the school district in which the charter school is located, taking into account the composition of the pupil population that is served at the charter school.

  5. Qualified for an alternative accountability system pursuant to Education Code section 52052(h).

     

    Assembly Bill 1808 recently amended Education Code section 52052(f) which now states:

    For any program identified in law that utilized a calculation pursuant to the former Academic Performance Index established pursuant to this section, as this section read on January 1, 2018, the 2013 growth calculation shall be applied for those purposes. For purposes of paragraphs (1) to (3), inclusive, of subdivision (b) of Section 47607, alternative measures that show increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils schoolwide and among numerically significant pupil subgroups shall be used.

     

[1] Numerically significant pupil subgroups include Ethnic subgroups, Socioeconomically Disadvantaged pupils, English Learners, Pupils with Disabilities, Foster Youth, and Homeless Youth. Per Ed Code section 52052, a subgroup is numerically significant if it consists of at least 30 pupils (15 pupils for foster or homeless youth).

[2] Items 1 3 have been superseded by Education Code section 52052(f).

Plans for Improvement

 

Per California Code of Regulations section 11966.4(b)(1), when considering a petition for renewal, the district governing board shall consider the past performance of the schools academics, finances, and operations in evaluating the likelihood of future success, along with any future plans for improvement. At the public hearing conducted on September 25, 2018, and in the renewal documents, Empower has identified the following steps to increase student performance on state assessments:

  • In 2017 implemented training in small group math instruction (Guided Math). Students receive instruction in small groups, and the centers incorporate math fluency, reasoning/problem solving, and number sense.

  • Implemented Number Talks in 2017 to encourage academic discourse among students to share the various approaches to the problem sets. This encourages students to use their number sense, mental math skills, and recognize that there are a variety of methods to solving a math problem.

  • In the summer of 2018, prior to the start of the school year, all instructional staff attended a three-day, Cognitively Guided Instruction (CGI) training. CGI is a student-centered approach to teaching math where the teacher first allows students to explore how they would solve a problem, prior to teaching any algorithms. CGI was aligned to the small guided math group structure.

After reviewing the information contained in tables 9-22, staff has determined that Empower has demonstrated increases in student academic achievement to support a renewal of its charter. The school made progress in its schoolwide ELA results, in all subgroups in ELA, and in the majority of its subgroups in Math.

BACKGROUND: The Charter Schools Facilities Program provides funding to construct new charter school facilities or to rehabilitate charter facilities at district-owned sites.  In June of 2016, the Board of Education adopted an annual resolution in support of the program and directing the authorized district representative to apply for eligibility, grants, and state funding under this program. 

 

In November of 2016, the voters of the State of California approved Proposition 51, a $9 billion bond measure for public school construction. $500 million of this amount is allocated for charter school projects.  

 

In June of 2017, the District submitted funding applications for nine charter schools, including the six mentioned above.   The State will provide, as grant funding, 50% of the approved costs for facilities, and the District will be responsible for the other 50 percent of the approved costs for the local match.  For FY 2018-2019, the District will receive $6,962,261 in Prop 51 funds to match the District’s contribution of $6,962,261.  The District is using Proposition S funds and Proposition Z funds, the latter which has a $350 million set aside for charters, as the local match.  For each of the six charters, no loan is required.   For the next two fiscal years after 2018-2019, the District may potentially receive an additional $62,660,352 in Prop 51 funds for the six charter schools.  To be eligible and to receive Proposition 51 funds under the program, a Memorandum of Understanding must be approved by each of the charter schools, the two state agencies, and San Diego Unified School District.   

  1. San Diego Cooperative is currently located on Linda Vista Annex campus, 7260 Linda Vista Road, San  Diego, California 921 I 1 (Attachment 1 – San Diego Cooperative MOU)
  2. San Diego Global Vision Academy is currently located on Adams Elementary School campus, 4672 35th Street, San Diego, CA 92116 (Attachment 2 – San Diego Global Vision MOU)
  3. America’s Finest is currently located on Mead Elementary School campus, 750 45th Street, San Diego, CA 92102 (Attachment 3 – America’s Finest MOU)
  4. The O’Farrell Community School is currently located on O'Farrell campus, 6130 Skyline Drive, San Diego, CA 92114 (Attachment 4 – O’Farrell MOU)
  5. Albert Einstein Academy [on behalf of Albert Einstein Academy Charter Elementary] is currently located on Brooklyn campus, 3035 Ash Street, San Diego, CA 92102 (Attachment 5 – Einstein MOU)
  6. Gompers Preparatory Academy is currently located on Gompers (West) campus, 1005 47th Street, San Diego, CA 92102  (Attachment 6 – Gompers MOU)

The six attached MOUs require the District to comply with Education Code 17078.62. That statute provides that the funded project shall be made available to the existing charter school until it is no longer needed by that charter school as a first priority. If the existing charter school has its charter revoked, or it is not renewed, there is a six-month waiting period before any other entity may occupy the facility, during which time the existing charter may appeal the revocation or non-renewal. Thereafter, as a second priority, the facility must be made available to another qualifying charter school under the same terms as it was made available to the previous charter. Only at such time as the facility is no longer needed for charter school facilities may it be re-occupied by the District.

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable. However, advisory committees were consulted during the development of the LCAP.

 

BACKGROUND:

 

As part of California's school accountability system aligned with the Local Control Funding Formula (LCFF) and the Local Control and Accountability Plan (LCAP), accountability results will be reported via the California School Dashboard (Dashboard). In addition to several state indicators (e.g., student scores from the Smarter Balanced assessments, English learner progress, graduation rates), Local Educational Agencies (LEAs) are required to report outcomes on four local indicators that apply to LEAs only, not schools:

 

  1. Appropriately Assigned Teachers, Access to Curriculum-Aligned Instructional Materials, and Safe, Clean and Functional School Facilities (State Priority 1)
    • Standard: LEA annually measures its progress in meeting the Williams Settlement requirements at all of its school sites, as applicable, and promptly addresses any complaints or other deficiencies identified throughout the academic year, as applicable.
  2. Implementation of State Academic Standards (State Priority 2)
    • Standard: LEA annually measures its progress implementing state academic standards.
  3. Parent Engagement (State Priority 3)
    • Standard: LEA annually measures its progress in (1) seeking input from parents in decision making and (2) promoting parental participation in programs.
  4. School Climate (State Priority 6)
    • Standard: LEA administers a local climate survey at least every other year that provides a valid measure of perceptions of school safety and connectedness, such as the California Healthy Kids Survey, to students in at least one grade within the grade span(s) that the LEA serves (e.g., K-5, 6-8, 9-12).
  5. Access to a Broad Course of Study (State Priority 7)
    • Standard: Local educational agencies (LEAs) annually measure their progress in the extent to which students have access to, and are enrolled in, a broad course of study.

Prior to finalizing information reported via the Dashboard, LEAs are required to have their governing boards review the information at a regularly scheduled public meeting. The information below presents some new information and also supplements information that was included in the 2018–19 LCAP that was adopted by the Board of Education on June 26, 2018. 

 

The three performance levels for the local indicators are: Met, Not Met, and Not Met for Two or More Years. To report that the standard is met on a local indicator, LEAs must demonstrate that they have collected and reported performance data for each local indicator. This agenda item fulfills the requirements and therefore, the district has met the standard for each of the local indicators.

RECOMMENDATION:

Approve recommendations of the Interdivisional Curriculum Committee (ICC).  The course recommendations are detailed on the attached exhibit and consist of four college courses and one request to offer a pilot course.

 

The ICC recommends:

 

  1. Add Community College courses districtwide (CITY-PHIL102B) Intro to Philosophy: Values, (MIRA-MATH 255) Differential Equations, (MESA-ARTF 109) Modern Art, (DRAM-105) Intro to Dramatic Arts.
  2. Piloting IB Environmental Systems and Societies SL (HP) (6369,6370) at Mission Bay High School

 

ICC recommendations are based on the following criteria: (1) clear correlation to State academic standards; (2) an evaluation plan to judge the efficacy of the pilot course; (3) applicable fulfillment of University of California 'a-g' requirements; and (4) accordance with State education code provisions.

 

The ICC voted on this item on October 3, 2018.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: Any costs associated with the proposed site adopted courses will be supported by the site.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND:

The ICC is responsible for the assessment and recommendation of requests pertaining to the curriculum included in the district's Course of Study.  The ICC reviews and recommends new courses, deletion of courses, and changes to approved courses to the Board of Education. It ensures that all courses are rigorous and provide students with multiple pathways to graduation, college, and career. Revisions to the Course of Study are aligned with LCAP Goal 2.3.a.  For 2018-19, the Committee is composed of the following members who are elected from among their peers, as stipulated by Bylaws that were adopted in August 2014:

 

  • 50 percent school site personnel, including two high school principals, one middle school principal, one elementary school principal, one secondary counselor, one secondary registrar, and the iHigh Virtual Academy principal.

 

  • 50 percent central office personnel:  four program managers and three directors.

23. Local Interagency Agreement with San Diego Regional Center and San Diego County Special Education Local Plan Areas and San Diego County Superintendent of Schools for California Early Start Program; BUDGETED: N/A

Nov 13, 2018 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type

RECOMMENDATION: Approve Local Interagency Agreement with San Diego Regional Center (SDRC) and San Diego County Special Education Local Plan Areas and San Diego County Superintendent of Schools for California Early Start Program to provide the roles and responsibilities of SDRC and Local Educational Agency (LEAs) for children birth to thirty-six months of age eligible for services under California Early Start program (PS19-0297-18). This Agreement will be in effect until significant changes necessitate that it will be jointly modified by SDRC and the LEAs.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: California Early Start is a federally funded program through Part C of the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA). The program is designed to ensure that eligible infants and toddlers and their families receive evaluation and assessment of their current functioning, and coordinated services early enough to make a difference in development.

 

Early intervention services are planned and delivered to help prevent or lessen the need for specialized services later in the childs life. The goal is to help answer questions and concerns about each childs development and to assure that infants and toddlers (ages 0-3 years) meet their highest potential. Services include medical diagnosis/evaluation; physical, occupational and speech therapy; special education instruction; social services, counseling and home visits.

 

The San Diego Regional Center (SDRC) provides service coordination, evaluations to determine eligibility and assessments for Individualized Family Service Plan (IFSP) development. The IFSP is a family-focused, outcome-oriented plan written to address the infant/toddlers developmental needs and family concerns.

 

The local Interagency Agreement between San Diego Regional Center and San Diego County Special Education Local Plan Areas and Superintendent of Schools San Diego County Office of Education for the California Early Start Program outlines the roles and responsibilities of SDRC and Local Educational Agency (LEAs) for children birth to thirty-six months of age eligible for services under California Early Start program. This interagency agreement has been in effect, but it was due for its three-year review/revision. Below are the substantive changes made, agreed upon and reviewed by the Part C interagency committee in conjunction with SDRC and LEAs attorney representatives:

  1. The entire document was reformatted to a side-by-side format for easier reference regarding the corresponding responsibilities of SDRC and the LEAs.
  2. The Preface (page 3) identifies all of the applicable laws and regulations related to Early Start which are covered in the body of the document.
  3. Only the required elements of a Part C Interagency Agreement are included.
  4. The Interagency Agreement no longer includes appendices.
  5. Services provided by the LEAs are referred to as early/special education services throughout the document.

This Interagency Agreement fulfills requirements of the 20 USC Section 1431 et seq.; 34 CFT Part 303, et seQ.; 14 CCR Sections 95001, et seq.; 17 CCR 52000, et seq.; 5 CCR Part 30; and Educational Code, section 56026.

 

This Interagency Agreement will be in effect until significant changes necessitate that it will be jointly modified by SDRC and the LEAs. The Agreement will be reviewed annually at a regularly scheduled Part C Administrative Team meeting. At three year intervals, the LEA and SDRC representative will update and amend the Agreement and obtain the required signatures of all parties.

 

[Originator/Contact: Sarah Ott, Executive Director, Special Education, 619.725.7650, sott@sandi.net]

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: The above-named teacher has been issued a Designated Subjects, Career Technical Education teaching credential and has applied for Crosscultural, Language, and Academic Development (CLAD) waiver while he completes the coursework required to fulfill the English Learner Authorization and CLAD Certificate authorizing instruction to English Learners.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: California Education Code section 44253.1 requires all teachers to have a valid English Learner Authorization if assigned to a classroom that has one or more students designated as English Learners. Teachers who hold a bachelors degree or higher and have completed an approved teacher preparation program leading to the issuance of a regular education credential but do not hold an English Learner Authorization qualify for an Emergency CLAD Permit. The emergency CLAD permit allows qualified individuals to be employed while completing requirements for the English Learner Authorization/CLAD Certificate and showing progress toward obtaining the certificate or authorization with each renewal.

 

Pursuant to the California Commission on Teacher Credentialing Leaflet CL-5330 (10/14), Emergency CLAD permits may be reissued to an applicant two times, authorizing a maximum of three years of service. Teaching or service authorized by an Emergency CLAD Permit is restricted to schools operated by the employing agency that requests the permit.

BACKGROUND: The bleacher replacement project at Point Loma High School, 2335 Chatsworth Boulevard, San Diego, CA 92106 consists of the district furnished/contractor installed gym bleacher replacement and accessibility upgrades at Point Loma High School.

 

Pursuant to Public Contract Code Section 20111 (b), the district must publicly competitively bid any public project involving an expenditure of $15,000 or more. The notice calling for bids was published once a week for two successive weeks in accordance with Public Contract Code section 20112.

 

Bids were due and opened on October 18, 2018. The district received a total of six bids from Byrom-Davey, Inc., Conan Construction, Inc., FedVet Construction, Fordyce Construction, Inc., GEM Industrial Electric, Inc., and Otero Construction Inc. After evaluating the bids, staff determined Otero Construction Inc., to be the lowest responsive and responsible bidder.

BACKGROUND: In 2013, the Environmental Sustainability Advisory Committee (ESAC) was formed at the request of the Board of Education to discuss a wide range of environmental sustainability initiatives to support Vision 2020. On July 8, 2014 and January 20, 2015, the ESAC presented 13 “Dream Big” ideas to the board which included solar energy installations as one of the most effective ways of reducing greenhouse gas emissions and utility costs. The 13 "Dream Big" ideas, including solar energy, were subsequently approved by the board on July 14, 2015.

 

Thereafter, on September 14, 2015, the district publicly advertised Request for Qualifications (RFQ) No. PS-16-0433-02 for the prequalification of firms to participate in subsequent Request for Proposals (RFP) for the Design-Build Delivery of Solar Power Generation Systems. The RFQ was advertised in the San Diego Daily Transcript and posted on DemandStar to 163 subscribers.

 

Five firms responded by the closing date of October 8, 2015, and were evaluated on their prequalification submittals. Four firms qualified to participate in the RFP process for the initial eight sites (PS-17-0144-02 and PS-17-0128-02) in Round 1, and additional projects being added in subsequent years. The four prequalified firms are: Borrego Solar Systems, Inc. (Borrego), ENGIE Services U.S. Inc (formerly Opterra Energy Services, hereinafter “ENGIE”), SunPower Corporation, Systems (SunPower), and Rosendin Electric, Inc. (Rosendin).

 

On September 13, 2016, the Board approved Master Agreements with ENGIE (PS-17-0144-02) and SunPower (PS-17-0128-02) to provide design-build services for installation of solar power generation systems at seven sites. Firm selection was based on a competitive solicitation process which was detailed on the September 13, 2016 board report.

 

The eighth site from Round 1, Penn Elementary School, was not assigned to a firm on the aforementioned Master Agreements and was reserved for a firm that ultimately decided not to enter into an agreement with the district. Thus, on December 13, 2016, the Board approved assignment of Penn Elementary School site to ENGIE for completion of the solar project under the terms of the agreement (PS-17-0512-02).

 

On September 14, 2017 the subsequent RFP (phase two) No. PS-18-0281-06 for Design-Build Solar power generation at 10 sites was issued to the four prequalified firms.

 

On September 25, 2018, the Board approved a Master Agreement with ENGIE (PS-18-0281-06) to provide design-build services for installation of solar power generation systems at six of the 10 phase two sites in the subsequent RFP issued to the four prequalified firms on September 14, 2017. Firm selection was based on a competitive solicitation process which was detailed on the September 25, 2018 board report.

 

The attached Master Agreement is for design-build services for installation of solar power generation systems at one of the 10 phase two sites (Bell Middle School) in the subsequent RFP issued on September 14, 2017. Once complete, the solar system at Bell Middle School is estimated to produce approximately 756,900 kilowatt-hours (756,900 kWh) electricity each year that will offset CO2 greenhouse gas emissions and utility costs (approximately $213,665.00 annually based on current utility rates).

 

Contract negotiations are continuing for the remaining three of the 10 sites at this time (CPMA, De Portola Middle School, and Madison High School), and will be submitted to a future board for approval upon completion.

 

The Proposed Project involves the installation of ground-mount solar PV arrays and utility trenching to connect the solar PV system to the grid at existing electric main service and sub panel connections. The solar PV system would be installed in two general locations on the Bell MS campus including adjacent to the existing track and athletic field in the northwest corner of the school site, and east of the existing baseball field in the north central portion of the campus. All solar PV systems would be ground-mount arrays within paved areas and would be located outside the footprint of the decommissioned solid waste landfill footprint. The individual solar PV panels would be constructed of dark-colored (usually blue or black) materials and covered with anti-reflective coatings. The Proposed Project would be designed to ensure that all existing ADA accessible paths of travel are maintained or reconfigured as prescribed by code. Electrical transmission lines would be installed in an underground conduit and would extend from the combiner to the main electrical service in one of the existing school buildings. All affected hardscape and/or landscape areas would be restored to pre-project conditions once construction is complete.

 

Procedurally, the district plans to issue separate Notices to Proceed (NTPs) against the Agreements as the work arises at each site. The NTPs are incorporated by reference into the Agreements and may be amended or ratified from time to time, as Amendments to the Agreements. The selected solar firms will also be tasked with commissioning each solar system for two years. After the initial two-year commissioning period, district staff will perform any necessary maintenance and operation services.

 

The proposed award of this contract for design build services for solar power generation projects at Bell Middle School are subject to the requirements of the California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA), Public Resources Code (PRC) section 21000 et. seq., and its implementing Guidelines (California Code of Regulations, Title 14, Division 6, Chapter 3, sections 15300.2 et. seq., as amended), because it authorizes construction of the above mentioned projects in accordance with the terms and specifications that were publicly bid and no further discretionary action is required by the board in order for these projects to proceed.

 

California Government Code section 4217.10, et seq. allows school districts to construct energy conservation projects or to enter into other leases or contracts relating to the financing, construction, operation or use of alternate energy type facilities in any manner authorized under existing law. Prior to awarding or entering into an agreement or lease, a public agency may request proposals from qualified persons and, after evaluating these proposals, a public agency may award a contract on the basis of experience of the contractor, the type of technology employed by contractor, the cost to the local agency, and any other relevant considerations.

 

ENVIRONMENTAL REVIEW: On September 7, 2018, the District made the draft MND available for a 30 day review at the following locations: San Diego Unified School District, Physical Plant Operations Center, Annex Room 5, 4860 Ruffner Street, San Diego, CA 92111; Skyline Hills Branch Library, 7900 Paradise Valley Rd, San Diego, CA 92114; Bell Middle School Main Office, 620 Briarwood Road, San Diego, CA 92139; and Online at: www.sandiegounified.org/environmental-reviews.

 

The Draft IS/MND evaluated the following environmental issues: aesthetics, agriculture and forestry resources, air quality, biological resources, cultural resources, geology and soils, greenhouse gas emissions, hazards and hazardous materials, hydrology and water quality, land use and planning, mineral resources, noise, population and housing, public services, recreation, transportation/traffic, tribal cultural resources, and utilities and service systems. Mitigation measures are proposed to reduce potential significant environmental impacts to less than significant. These proposed measures are summarized in the attached Mitigation Monitoring and Reporting Program (MMRP) (Attachment 3).

 

No comment letters were received and no edits to the Draft IS/MND were required.

 

The Final IS/MND (Attachment 2) and MMRP (Attachment 3) was prepared in accordance with CEQA and the Guidelines for Implementation of CEQA. A copy of the Final IS/MND for the Bell Middle School Solar Photovoltaic Project has been provided to the board for review prior to the public meeting. The approved Final IS/MND will be located at San Diego Unified School District (Physical Plant Operations Annex, Room 5), 4860 Ruffner Street, San Diego, CA 92111. The Final IS/MND is also available online at the Environmental Reviews/Studies page at: www.sandiegounified.org/environmental-reviews.

On November 15, 2016, the District publicly advertised a Request for Qualifications and Proposals (RFQ/P) for comprehensive supplemental support services. The RFQ/P was advertised in the San Diego Daily Journal, Union Tribune, Asian Journal, La Prensa San Diego and San Diego Voice & Viewpoint. The RFQ/P was also posted on DemandStar and forwarded to interested firms in the Districts Facilities Business Outreach database.

 

Four firms, AECOM Technical Services, Gafcon, Inc., Harris & Associates and Vanir Construction Management, Inc. responded on the due date of December 15, 2016. The Evaluation Committee carefully reviewed the fully-burdened hourly rates plus the calculation of the extended rate for each projected number of personnel per position description submitted by each of the three firms.

 

Because of the level of expertise and volume of specialized services required, the three firms will be required to provide support on an as-required basis. The specialized services include: engineering, geotechnical engineering, environmental engineering, program analysis, architectural engineering design and construction management, systems development and, and other related services for planned and ongoing projects.

 

Proposition S was approved on November 4, 2008, and Proposition Z was approved on November 6, 2012. Subsequently, the Board of Education authorized the issuance of over $1.9 billion in general obligation bonds to implement Propositions S and Z projects. The Propositions S and Z capital bond program has an ambitious schedule for the planning and construction of identified projects. The scheduled scope of general obligation bond funded capital improvement work includes new school buildings and classroom modernizations, fire safety system improvements, classroom technology upgrades, and energy efficiency projects.


Each proposed Propositions S and Z bond funded agreement has a three-year term with two, one-year options to renew. During the initial agreement period, the Districts Propositions S and Z capital bond program expects to put in place approximately $850 million in new school facilities and facility school renovation projects. While the contract values may appear significant, they actually represent a small percentage of the overall program and are well below industry standards for such a large program. Moreover, it is anticipated the three agreements will encourage efficiency because of inherent competition among the firms for the District's business.

BACKGROUND: These terminations for convenience are solely for the District's administrative convenience as an efficient way to make changes and updates, instead of executing amendments.  These terminations for convenience are not a reflection of vendor performance, but an administrative requirement to avoid concurrent agreements with a single vendor.

 

On November 4, 2008, and November 6, 2012, respectively, residents of San Diego County voted to approve Propositions S and Z (together the Bond Program) for capital improvement school projects. In an effort to provide a quality school in every neighborhood, the District is using Proposition S and Proposition Z funds to repair, renovate, and revitalize District schools. Bond projects include classroom technology; safety and security upgrades; Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) upgrades; new/renovated facilities for College, Career and Technical Education facilities; temporary classrooms replaced by permanent classrooms; air conditioning; ADA upgrades and improvements to athletic facilities; turf fields; and other capital improvements at District and charter schools throughout the District.

 

Design services are an integral part of the construction process, and a large number of qualified firms will be necessary to provide the services required. In 2012, the District contracted with 24 architectural firms for assigned work. These agreements and amendments expire in the year and it is critical that the District maintain some capacity to issue task orders as the work progresses. The District does not possess the necessary resources in-house to perform the services.

 

On July 24, 2018, the District publicly advertised Request for Qualifications (RFQ) PS-19-0054-24 for competitive proposals. The advertisement appeared in the (1) The Daily Transcript, (2) San Diego Union-Tribune; (3) San Diego Voice and Viewpoint; and (4) La Prensa San Diego. The RFQ was also posted on DemandStar to 502 vendors and forwarded to interested firms in the Districts Facilities Business Outreach database.

 

Thirty-five firms responded by the closing date of August 17, 2018, and were evaluated by a qualified Evaluation Committee on the basis of best value, including technical ability and price structure. Based on the final ratings of the panel, 21 firms are recommended for contract award.

 

An initial eight firms are recommended for contract award on November 13, 2018, and the remaining thirteen firms will be presented for Board approval at a later date when negotiations are complete. In order to execute these Agreements, the District must first terminate the existing agreements with these same firms as they cannot be party to two contracts for the same services concurrently. For this reason, these terminations for convenience are not a reflection of performance of the architects, but simply an administrative requirement for the District.

In order for the District to complete the Bond Program, it is essential to have the architectural agreements in place. Lead times for construction projects are substantial with project design typically lasting 14 months in length after the District has issued a Notice to Proceed (NTP) to the architect, plus an additional 12 months of contract administration needed to complete each project. Design of planned projects must be commenced well in advance of when these projects are actually constructed because the designs have to be ready for bid purposes when the funds are released for construction. Design costs represent a small fraction of the cost of any construction project, but this work helps keep project costs to a minimum. Funds allocated to each contract are estimated over a three-year period, and tasks are authorized on a case-by-case basis. This process allows the district to schedule projects without delays and avoids unnecessary funding issues. Any funds remaining at term end are returned to the original source.

 

California Government Code section 4525, et seq., grants the District the authority to contract with and employ persons for the furnishing of architectural and landscape architectural services if such persons are specially trained, experienced, and competent to perform the special services requested.

EXCESS VEHICLE SALES

RECOMMENDATION: Authorize the utilization of State of California Multiple Award Schedule (CMAS) Contract to purchase five Ford Transit Vans (CMAS Contract 1-18-23-23A; GD19-0499-19). Authorize the execution of any documents necessary to effectuate this authorization. The term of this authorization is November 14, 2018 through February 28, 2019.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: Total not-to-exceed amount: $125,000.00. Budget String: 5650-96000-00-6495-3600-0000-01000-000.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: The District Mail Delivery Department has been providing mail delivery, bank deposits, urgent and emergency delivery services Districtwide utilizing District-owned vans for over 18 years. These vans have an average of over 250,000 miles each. The purchase of the five new Ford Transit Vans will ensure that the services provided by the mail department continue to operate flawlessly while supporting the safety of district drivers. The new vans also produce less greenhouse gas emissions contributing to the District's Sustainability Action Plan (SAP). San Diego Unifieds Sustainability Action Plans, Dream Big Solutions for a Sustainable Future were developed to help reduce the Districts environmental footprint with a goal towards net zero waste.

 

Under Public Contract Code section 20118, the governing board has determined that it is in the best interests of the district to utilize this "piggyback" contract to purchase supplies. The statute provides that the District may purchase personal property from contracts already competitively bid by another public agency. Additionally, pursuant to Public Contract Code 10298, local agencies may, without further competitive bidding, use State awarded contracts for the purchase of goods, information technology, and services for acquisitions authorized under Public Contract Code Section 10290.  

 

On July 8, 2014, the Board received the final report from the Environmental Sustainability Advisory Committee. Included in this report as a "Dream Big" idea was a recommended action to join or create larger purchasing cooperatives. A purchasing cooperative establishes various contracts which aggregate the total purchases from many government entities resulting in lower costs to governmental entities who then utilize these contracts.

BACKGROUND: The Board first approved offering Multiyear Facilities Use Permit Agreements (MFUPAs--former title of MFLAs) on October 6, 2009, to charter schools meeting certain criteria (have occupied District facilities; have demonstrated financial stability; have been through the renewal process at once; or were 'conversion charter schools' from previously District-run schools). Gompers Preparatory Academy Charter School is a conversion charter school from a previously District-run school, which currently operates at the 1005 47th Street, San Diego, California 92102.   The approval of this MFLA is contingent upon the Board's approval of the charter renewal for the same term.

 

Approval of the MFLA is considered a project under CEQA and is subject to the requirements of the California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA), Public Resources Code (PRC) section 21000 et. seq., and its implementing Guidelines (California Code of Regulations, Title 14, Division 6, Chapter 3, sections 15300.2 et. seq., as amended). On July 24, 2018, the Board approved the Gompers Preparatory Academy Athletic Facilities and Whole Site Modernization (WSM) project and directed staff to file a California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA) Notice of Exemption (NOE) with the County Recorder/Clerk, which occurred on July 25, 2018 (Attachment 1).

 

The NOE prepared for the Gompers Preparatory Academy Athletic Facilities and Whole Site Modernization Project analyzed the environmental impacts associated with the construction and operation of a new gymnasium facility, a dance/weight room area, locker room, walking/running track, tennis courts, the construction of a new two-story classroom building with 22 classrooms that will replace 28 existing portable classrooms, various site accessibility and security upgrades, and reconfiguration of the existing parking areas. The Proposed Project assumed buildout by 2023, with a total capacity of 1,319 students. Based on the foregoing, staff has determined that the proposed approval of the MFLA has been fully analyzed in the above mentioned NOE and no further CEQA review is required.

59. Determine that the Energy Efficiency Projects at 12 District Sites are Exempt from the California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA) Pursuant to CEQA Guidelines Section 15301 and 15302; Direct Staff to File the Notice of Exemption (NOE) with the San Diego County Recorder/Clerks Office; and Approve Agreement with Schneider Electric to Provide Design-Build Energy Efficient Projects as Turnkey Operations for Proposition 39 Capital Projects; BUDGETED: YES, PROPOSITION 39 FUNDS
Meeting
Nov 13, 2018 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Action (Consent)
Fiscal Impact
Yes
Dollar Amount
$5,816,049.11
Budgeted
Yes
Budget Source
Proposition 39 Funds

RECOMMENDATION: Determine that the energy efficiency projects at 12 district sites are exempt from the California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA) pursuant to CEQA Guidelines Section 15301 and 15302; direct staff to file the Notice of Exemption (NOE) with the San Diego County Recorder/Clerks Office; and approve Agreement with Schneider Electric to provide design/build energy efficient projects as turnkey operations (PS19-0125-52). The term of the Agreement is November 13, 2018 through March 31, 2020.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: Total not to exceed amount: $5,816,049.11 for the term of the Agreement. Budget String: 5548-62300-00-5711-8100-0000-01000-0000 Interprogram Services/job costs Prop 39 funding. $50.00 for CEQA NOE filing fees.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None. 

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND:

On November 6, 2013, Proposition 39, the California Clean Energy Jobs Act, was passed by voters. Under this initiative, schools are eligible for funding over the five years of the program beginning in fiscal year 2013-14. The California Energy Commission (CEC) is tasked to administer Prop 39 with the overarching approach that local education agencies first maximize energy efficiency, and then install clean on-site energy generation, and last, consider non-renewable energy projects. The Proposition 39 program funds a total of 59 sites consisting of 102 separate energy projects. These projects include interior and exterior LED lighting, HVAC replacement, HVAC controls and PV solar installations. This agreement focuses on 12 sites with a total of 16 projects. Five sites were awarded on a previous Request for Proposal (RFP) PS-18-0281-06 and 32 sites were contracted to install interior LED lighting. The goals of this program are to save energy, save general fund and reduce greenhouse gases.

 

The benefits of all Prop 39 energy efficiency projects are to:

  • Enhance the indoor environmental quality of schools in keeping with the districts main objective of improving the educational experience of students, teachers and staff.
  • Offset increased electrical consumption from newly installed bond funded classroom air conditioning systems.
  • Save money to enable the district to redirect funds toward educational purposes for many years to come.
  • Reduce greenhouse gases as specified in the districts "Climate Mitigation and Adaptation Goals."
  • Implement the Districts Dream Big Sustainability Goals adopted by the board of education in 2014 by implementing Zero Net Energy (Idea #4), install LED lighting (Idea #5) and install PV solar (Idea #3).

On September 15, 2015, the district publicly advertised Request for Qualifications (RFQ) No. PS-16-0541-57 for prequalification of firms to participate in an RFP for the design-build delivery of energy efficient projects as turnkey operations. The RFQ was advertised in the San Diego Daily Transcript and posted on DemandStar.

 

Seven firms responded by the closing date of October 1, 2015, and were evaluated on their prequalification submittals. The three firms that qualified (Schneider Electric, Noresco, and Barnhart-Reese) were invited to participate in the RFP No. PS19-0125-52, which was issued on July 2, 2018.

The three prequalified firms submitted their proposals by the closing date of August 7, 2018, and were scored by a qualified Evaluation Committee on the basis of best value. Five categories were scored for a possible total of 100 points for each vendor. The Committee considered (1) project budget, (2) design, (3) support/training, (4) exceptions, and (5) overall value. The members of the Evaluation Committee consisted of Darin Vey, Manager, Safety, Training and Environmental Compliance; Steve Ditto, Planning Manager; and Ron Coleman, Crew Leader II.

 

Based on the final ratings of the panel, one firm (Schneider Electric) was recommended for award to complete 16 projects at 12 sites: Bell Middle, Bethune K-8, Chollas/Mead Elementary, Ericson Elementary, Hickman Elementary, Knox Middle School, Mason Elementary, Penn Elementary, Rosa Parks Elementary, San Diego School of Creative and Performing Arts (SCPA), Sandburg Elementary, and the district's Transportation Center. The Committee rejected proposals from Noresco and Barnhart-Reese because they did not propose the best value.

 

Procedurally, the district plans to issue separate Notices to Proceed (NTPs) against the Agreement as the work arises at each site. The NTPs are incorporated by reference into the Agreement and may be amended or ratified from time to time, as Amendments to the Agreement. Schneider Electric will also be tasked with third-party commissioning of each energy efficient measure, as well as retro-commissioning of existing equipment. Upon completion of installation, commissioning and acceptance of the installed system as functioning as designed, district staff will perform any necessary maintenance and operations services.

 

Once complete, the Prop 39 projects at the aforementioned 12 sites are estimated to produce approximately 925,004 kWH of annual energy savings that will offset approximately $201,707 in utility costs annually based on current electricity rates.

 

California Government Code section 4217.10, et seq. allows school districts to construct energy conservation projects or to enter into other leases or contracts relating to the financing, construction, operation or use of alternate energy type facilities in any manner authorized under existing law. Prior to awarding or entering into an agreement or lease, a public agency may request proposals from qualified persons and, after evaluating these proposals, a public agency may award a contract on the basis of experience of the contractor, the type of technology employed by contractor, the cost to the local agency, and any other relevant considerations.

 

CEQA Analysis:

The proposed HVAC and lighting efficiency improvements at the 12 identified sites are exempt from further environmental review under the following CEQA categorical exemption classes:

 

Existing Facilities (Class 1) - Class 1 consists of the operation, repair, maintenance, permitting, leasing, licensing, or minor alteration of existing public or private structures, facilities, mechanical equipment, or topographical features. Existing facilities of both investor and publicly-owned utilities used to provide electric power, natural gas, sewerage, or other public utility services (CEQA Guidelines 15301[b]).

 

The HVAC and lighting efficiency improvements would occur within existing facilities where existing, but aging, HVAC and lighting equipment exists. Therefore, the application of a Class 1 categorical exemption is appropriate for the Proposed Project.

 

Replacement or Reconstruction (Class 2) - Class 2 consists of replacement or reconstruction of existing structures and facilities where the new structure will be located on the same site as the structure replaced and will have substantially the same purpose and capacity as the structure replaced, including replacement or reconstruction of existing utility systems and/or facilities involving negligible or no expansion of capacity (CEQA Guidelines 15302[c]).

 

The HVAC and lighting efficiency improvements would occur entirely within existing facilities where existing, but aging, HVAC and lighting equipment exists. The proposed improvements would not expand capacity or result in the change in use of the utility. Therefore, the application of a Class 2 categorical exemption is appropriate for the Proposed Project.

 

Exceptions to Use of a Categorical Exemption (CEQA Guidelines Section 15300.2):

Section 15300.2 of the State CEQA Guidelines specifies several exceptions to the use of a categorical exemption.

  1. Location. Classes 3, 4, 5, 6, and 11 are qualified by consideration of where the project is to be located a project that is ordinarily insignificant in its impact on the environment may in a particularly sensitive environment be significant. Therefore, these classes are considered to apply in all instances, except where the project may impact on an environmental resource of hazardous or critical concern where designated, precisely mapped, and officially adopted pursuant to law by federal, state, or local agencies.
  2. Cumulative Impact. All exemptions for these classes are inapplicable when the cumulative impact of successive projects of the same type in the same place, over time is significant.
  3. Significant Effect. A categorical exemption shall not be used for an activity where there is a reasonable possibility that the activity will have a significant effect on the environment due to unusual circumstances.
  4. Scenic Highways. A categorical exemption shall not be used for a project which may result in damage to scenic resources, including but not limited to trees, historic buildings, rock outcroppings, or similar resources, within a highway officially designated as a state scenic highway. This does not apply to improvements that are required as mitigation by an adopted negative declaration or certified EIR.
  5. Hazardous Waste Sites. A categorical exemption shall not be used for a project located on a site that is included on any list compiled pursuant to Section 65962.5 of the Government Code.
  6. Historical Resources. A categorical exemption shall not be used for a project that may cause a substantial adverse change in the significance of a historical resource.

 

Environmental Review: The following provides review of the potential environmental issues associated with the Proposed Project to ensure that the above exceptions are not relevant to the project.

  1. Location. The proposed HVAC and lighting efficiency improvements would be installed on existing district sites in urbanized communities. All areas on the sites where the HVAC and lighting efficiency improvements would be installed within existing disturbed areas. Therefore, none of the project sites are considered environmentally sensitive. Any ground disturbance would occur within disturbed soils. As such, the Proposed Project would not impact areas that have environmental resources of hazardous or critical concern. This exception does not apply to the project.
  2. Cumulative Impact. The improvements that would be implemented by the district at each project site are exempt from CEQA and therefore would not result in significant impacts. Construction activities are minor in scope and individually limited; consequently, their associated environmental effects would not be significant. Combined, the construction effects of the Proposed Project and any other unknown projects that may occur on- or off- each individual district site, would not be significant, and impacts would not be cumulatively considerable. The combined operational impacts of the Proposed Project and related projects would also be de minimis. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the Notice of Exemption.
  3. Significant Effect. There is no reasonable possibility that the Proposed Project would have a significant effect on the environment due to unusual circumstances. There is nothing unusual about the site of the proposed HVAC and lighting efficiency improvements or surrounding area. Additionally, HVAC and lighting equipment are not unusual for district sites and there is nothing unusual about the design or specifications of the HVAC and lighting efficiency improvements that could result in a significant effect on the environment.

Installation of the proposed HVAC and lighting efficiency improvements would not require the removal of any healthy, mature, or scenic trees. The project sites and surrounding neighborhoods are located within urbanized areas that do not support any sensitive vegetation that could be impacted by the Proposed Project. Any affected vegetation would be ornamental and used for landscaping.

  1. Scenic Highways. The project would not result in the demolition of existing structures or the construction of new facilities that would directly or indirectly affect an officially designated scenic highway or scenic resources near a scenic highway. There are no designated scenic resources or highways within one-quarter mile of any of the project sites. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the project.
  2. Hazardous Waste Sites. There are no district facilities located on a hazardous waste site that are included on any list compiled pursuant to Section 65962.5 of the Government Code (DTSC 2018a). Generally, the scope of work proposed for the installation of the HVAC and lighting efficiency improvements at each site will not result in activities that would expose workers or occupants to hazardous materials or existing hazardous materials releases. Additionally, there are no known active hazardous materials conditions on or adjacent to any of the project sites. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the project.
  3. Historical Resources. According to the CEQA Guidelines regarding historical resources, a substantial adverse change in the significance of a historical resource amounts to a significant impact on the environment (Guidelines 15064.5(b)). Accordingly, a substantial adverse change means demolition, destruction, relocation, or alteration of the resource or its immediate surroundings resulting in the significance of the resource being materially impaired. Of the 12 project sites, only Knox Middle School has the potential to be eligible for listing in the CRHR due to the building age of over 50 years old. However, the property is a typical example of a 1950s school. Designed by the firm of Wulff & Fifield, it does not appear to be associated with events that have made a significant contribution to the broad patterns of Californias history and cultural heritage; is not associated with the lives of persons important in our past; does not embody the distinctive characteristics of a type, period, region, or method of construction, nor does it represent the work of an important creative individual, or possess high artistic value; and has not yielded, and is unlikely to yield, information important in prehistory or history. The building does not appear eligible for listing in the CRHR and does not appear to meet the criteria of a historical resource per CEQA Guidelines (14 CCR 15064.5). Furthermore, the proposed improvements associated with the Proposed Project would replace existing utility equipment and would not materially alter existing buildings. Additionally, the likelihood of impacting either prehistoric or historic archeological resources is negligible for the current undertaking due because grading and trenching into non-native soils is not proposed.

Rescind Prior Authorization to Lease Ten Police Vehicles Approved September 4, 2018; Authorize and Approve Revised Five-Year Lease of Nine Ford Explorers (Year 1) and Up to Eight Ford Police Interceptors (Year 2) for Use by School Police; Authorize Disposal of Up to Nine Surplus Vehicles; Approve Leases Pursuant to the Terms of the E&I Cooperative Contract with Enterprise Fleet Management. BUDGETED: YES, SCHOOL POLICE FUNDS
Meeting
Nov 13, 2018 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Action (Consent)
Fiscal Impact
Yes
Dollar Amount
$675,424.00
Budget Source
School Police Department Funds

RECOMMENDATION: Rescind prior Authorization to lease ten police vehicles approved September 4, 2018; Authorize and Approve revised Five-Year Lease of nine Ford Explorers (Year 1) and up to eight Ford Police Interceptors (Year 2) for use by School Police; Authorize disposal of up to nine surplus vehicles; Approve Leases pursuant to the terms of the E&I Cooperative Contract with Enterprise Fleet Management Contract No. CNR01399 (RFP No: 683311); (GD19-0397-19). Authorize the execution of any documents necessary to effectuate the lease.  The term of each vehicle lease is five years. 

 

FISCAL IMPACT: Total not-to-exceed amount: Lease Agreement #1 (2019/20 2023/24) $281,800; Lease Agreement #2 (2020/21 2024/25): $393,624.  Budget string: 5605-00005-00-5853-8300-0000-01000-0000.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: In order to provide the mobility that is essential for school police to maintain order and security on and near school campuses, which facilitates a safe and secure environment for all students to learn, the district's fleet of police vehicles must be operationally ready and of a body style conducive to supporting current and future school police operations. This is essential in order to maximize the effectiveness of the district's sworn police officers.  The current fleet of school police vehicles, including unmarked vehicles, requires replacement due to their age, road-worthiness and increasing maintenance costs. While police vehicles are built to different standards than conventional street vehicles, their effective years of service are reduced by the effects of their usage as a law enforcement vehicle. In addition, the traditional, 4-door sedan body style of a law enforcement vehicle has been replaced with a law enforcement utility vehicle body style which better accommodates and supports the current and future operational requirements of a police officer. Providing vehicles to school police officers aids in the ability of the department to provide services when assigned to multiple school sites thus enabling school police to support the districts mission to provide a safe and secure environment for all students to learn. 

 

On September 4, 2018, the board authorized the lease of ten police vehicles with Enterprise Fleet Management based on the E&I Cooperative Contract.   The September 4, 2018 authorization provided the ability to lease four utility police interceptors, five SUVs, and one truck for a total of ten vehicles. Due to the expiration of the model year ordering cycle, the four utility police interceptors are no longer available. Therefore, staff is recommending that the new authorization for Year 1 be for nine unmarked Ford Explorers at an annual lease cost of $56,205.36.  The annual cost to lease in Year 1 under the revised authorization is approximately $12,000 less per year than the previously authorized annual lease cost of $69,089.00.  Staff anticipates procuring via lease up to eight Ford Police Interceptors once they are available for model year 2020 (Year 2).  The estimated costs for the Year 2 acquisition is $393,624, which is the total cost to lease over the five year term.  Thus, in the second year of the fleet replacement plan, the annual cost to the district is estimated at $191,045.  


 

At the end of the Year 1 lease term, the district may choose to purchase the vehicles at a cost of $5,529.80 per vehicle ($49,758.20 for all nine vehicles.)  The book value at the end of the five-year lease period is only 19 percent of the vehicles purchase price.  If the district were to return the vehicles to Enterprise at the end of the lease term, the district may be assessed a small amount although that is highly unlikely given the depreciated value of the vehicles at lease end. However, if the vehicles are valued at more than the depreciated value, for example at $10,000, the district would realize the difference between the book value and wholesale value.  That revenue could then be applied to a new lease. 

 

Approval of this item will allow the district to 1) enter into an open-ended, five-year lease for nine unmarked Ford Explorers in Year 1 and up to eight Ford Police Interceptors in Year 2; and 2) authorize staff to sell up to nine vehicles currently in the fleet as they are replaced by the newly leased vehicles.

62. Third Amendment to Agreement [non-NMTC Sites] with SD Solar I, LLC, as Assignee of AES Distributed Energy, Inc. Formerly Known as Main Street Power Company, Inc., to Continue Providing Long-Term Energy Purchase at Various Schools and Administration Sites; and Second Amendment to Agreement [NMTC Sites] with MSP Master Tenant II, LLC, as assignee of AES Distributed Energy, Inc. Formerly Known as Main Street Power Company, Inc., to Continue Providing Long-Term Energy Purchase at Various Schools and Administration Sites; BUDGETED: N/A

Nov 13, 2018 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Action (Consent)
Fiscal Impact
No

RECOMMENDATION: Ratify Third Amendment to Agreement [non-NMTC Sites] with SD Solar I, LLC, as assignee of AES Distributed Energy, Inc. formerly known as Main Street Power Company, Inc., to continue providing long-term energy purchase at various school and administration sites (GD-11-0461-64, Part-2); and Ratify Second Amendment to Agreement [NMTC Sites] with MSP Master Tenant II, LLC, as assignee of AES Distributed Energy, Inc. formerly known as Main Street Power Company, Inc., to continue providing long-term energy purchase at various school and administration sites GD-11-0461-64, Part-1). The terms of these Agreements are unchanged by the Third Amendment Part 2 and Second Amendment Part 1, and continues to be 20 years after the Commercial Operations start date.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None. 

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None. 

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND:  Government Code section 4217.10 et seq. allows a school district to enter into an energy management agreement on terms that are determined by its governing board to be in its best interest. In or about 2009, six companies responded to the Districts Request for Proposals.

 

On May 25, 2010, the board approved a non-binding Letter of Intent that allowed Main Street Power Company to secure rebates through the California Solar Initiative and gave its approval to enter into negotiations with Main Street Power Company to establish a Solar Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) with the district. The negotiations resulted into two PPAs: one PPA is designated as New Markets Tax Credits (NMTC) available to Main Street Power for qualified low income areas as defined in IRS Code and, another PPA for the balance of the areas designated as non-NMTC.

 

On September 14, 2010, the Board approved these two PPAs for NMTC sites and non-NTMC sites, allowing Main Street Power Company to own, install, and maintain solar panels on roofs of designated district properties, and then sell the energy generated from the solar panels back to the District at a discounted rate compared to SDG&Es rate. The solar panels pertain to 36 District sites. At the end of the 20-year agreement, unless otherwise agreed by the parties, Main Street Power Company will remove the solar panels at its own expense.

 

On May 15, 2012, the Board approved the clarification and modification to the PPAs related to the solar installation impact to the roofing systems as required by Division of State Architects (DSA). As such, the First Amendments clarify the maintenance and inspection obligations and also more clearly define the roles and responsibilities of the District and Main Street Power Company, Inc. in the implementation and ongoing administration of these agreements.

 

On March 11, 2014, the Board approved the second amendment for the non-NMTC sites (6 sites), which updated the actual solar system installation size, production, and cost data in the agreements; and provided clarification and update of the related system size terms and calculations. The original systems sizes were larger and therefore correcting to the actual sizes installed with site and design requirements that reduced the sizes is appropriate for this PPA agreement. The nomenclature of the system cost calculation for termination and/or buyout by the District is also clarified by referring to the system size calculation in watts. The definition of "Termination Price" in Exhibit A is removed, since section 19.2 already defined the termination price in the agreements. The changes were projected to have marginal impact on costs or savings, as electric rates have been increased beginning September of 2013 and the smaller systems were projected to provide a higher percentage of energy during peak cost periods.

 

If District desires to perform certain structural alterations, repairs or modifications on the buildings identified on Exhibit A, the PPAs require the District to notify Power Providers and reach a mutual written agreement on the schedule and payment to Power Providers, but does not discuss a process to do so. For this reason, the District entered into this Third Amendment to Agreement [non-NMTC Sites] (GD-11-0461-64, Part-2) and entered into this Second Amendment to Agreement [NMTC Sites] (GD-11-0461-64, Part-1) to provide for more detail on the parties roles and responsibilities.  To date, District has requested temporary removal, storage, and reinstallation of certain solar photovoltaic generating facilities at Pershing and Adams school sites and work has been completed/is currently being performed. These amendments also add another funding source to pay Power Providers when they undertake these tasks.

BACKGROUND: These transactions are submitted to the Board for review pursuant to Education Code sections 17604 and 17605 and under its delegation of authority to the District Strategic Sourcing and Contracts Officer. To allow for efficiency in the administration of a large urban school district, California Education Code section 17605 specifically allows a school district to delegate limited purchasing power, i.e., for purchases no greater than $90,200 (for the year 2018) for supplies, materials, apparatus, equipment, non-construction services not greater than $90,200, and construction services less than $15,000. For this reason, these types of transactions must be reviewed by the board within 60 days of the date of the transaction under Education Code section 17605. Pursuant to the authority delegated to the District Strategic Sourcing and Contracts Officer on June 19, 2018, these purchase orders have been released to the respective vendors and are being submitted for review by the Board at this time. Additionally, the attached agreements were signed pursuant to the delegation of authority and, as required by Education Code section 17604, must be approved or ratified by the Board of Education.

 

Thus, the District has met the requirements of Education Code section 17605 with this process of reporting out the specified purchase orders under $90,200 (for the year 2018) that are not associated with any previously-approved board contracts.
